        "slider_hK6zKc": {
          "type": "slider",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "<p>Proven to visually improve</p>",
            "text": "<p>Q-Rejuvalight Pro utilizes a 630 nm red LED, a wavelength clinically shown to boost collagen synthesis and improve wrinkle depth and skin texture. In a 2009 trial, participants experienced a <strong>31% increase</strong> in type‑1 procollagen production, with<strong>over 90%</strong> also seeing a reduction in wrinkle depth and surface roughness <strong>after just 12 treatments</strong>. The trial also found that 87% of participants demonstrated lower Fitzpatrick wrinkling scores,<br/>[line]</p><p><strong>About the clinical trial</strong></p><p>8-week single-blinded split-face trial with participants aged 27 to 79. Results measured after 12 treatments using profilometry and Fitzpatrick wrinkle severity scoring.</p><p>Reference: Lee, Soo-Young, et al. \"Regulation of Skin Collagen Metabolism in Vitro Using a Pulsed 660 nm LED Light Source: Clinical Correlation with a Single-Blinded Study.\" Journal of Investigative Dermatology, vol. 129, no. 12, Dec. 2009, pp. 2751–2759.</p>",
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/q_rejuv_ab_1.webp",
            "button_label": "Fine Lines & Wrinkles",
            "button_label_image": "Fine Lines & Wrinkles"
          }
        },
        "slider_KYFhBe": {
          "type": "slider",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "<p>Proven to visually improve</p>",
            "text": "<p>A 2007 clinical study found that red LED therapy visibly improved signs of sun damage, including skin texture and tone, <strong>after just 9 treatments</strong>. By week 12, 91% of participants reported brighter, more even skin, and 82% noticed smoother texture. These results support the skin-renewing benefits of red light wavelengths used in the Q-Rejuvalight Pro.<br/>[line]</p><p><strong>About the clinical trial</strong></p><p>5‑week single-arm trial with 13 photoaged participants. Results measured after 9 treatments via clinical photography and patient satisfaction scores at 6, 9, and 12 weeks</p><p>Reference: Russell, Bethany A., et al. \"The Effects of Red and Infrared LED Light on Photoaged Skin.\" Journal of Cosmetic Dermatology, vol. 6, no. 3, Sept. 2007, pp. 189–194.</p>",
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/q_rejuv_ab_2.webp",
            "button_label": "Dark Spots & Skin Tone",
            "button_label_image": "Dark Spots"
          }
        },
        "slider_jT4fBt": {
          "type": "slider",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "<p>Proven to visually improve</p>",
            "text": "<p>Q-Rejuvalight Pro combines blue (415 nm) and red (630 nm) LED wavelengths that are proven to improve mild to severe acne. A 2006 study found that after 8 sessions over 4 weeks, participants saw a <strong>46% reduction </strong>in lesion count at 4 weeks and an impressive <strong>81% reduction</strong> at 12 weeks, with minimal side effect.<br/>[line]</p><p><strong>About the clinical trial</strong></p><p>4-week trial with 24 participants with mild to severe acne. Results measured after 8 treatments via lesion counts at weeks 2, 4, 8, and 12, along with dermatologist evaluation and patient self-assessment.</p><p>Reference: Gold, Michael H., et al. \"Combination Blue (415 nm) and Red  (633 nm) LED Phototherapy in the Treatment of Mild to Severe Acne Vulgaris.\" Journal of Cosmetic and Laser Therapy, vol. 8, no. 2, June 2006, pp. 71–75.</p>",
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/q_rejuv_ab_3.webp",
            "button_label": "Dark Spots & Skin Tone",
            "button_label_image": "Acne & Breakouts"
          }
        }
